Thanks, Joe. It needs some finetuning, and as a baby Wiki project I will
nurture it like a small plant. :-)

I need to throw in some links, or I could. I believe it's Wiki style not to
have inline links that deliver you to an external website (in fact, I know
it's not). So I don't know how to point at websites on Marine units that are
mentioned, within the body of the text.

I also can pin down some dates better. And provide some context. One reason
USS RALEIGH was so ready, and the Marines were so ready, is that we were all
slated for a northern Europe exercise - 4th MEB at the time was the Marine
contribution to NATO, after all. When Saddam invaded Kuwait, we were pretty
much packing our bags already, so to speak. The powers that be just said,
boys, dress for warmer climes.

The cruise book specifically says:

"15 days after Iraq invaded Kuwait, the USS Raleigh embarked units of 3rd Bn
2nd Marines and 1st Bn 10th Marines. Ready on short notice, they were among
the first amphibious units to deploy for DESERT SHIELD".

The Suez canal transit was September 8th, according to the book.

I am considering whether or not to include a small photo. For copyright
reasons I can't currently include one from the cruise book, which has some
great pics. But I do have quite a few of my own that showcase the old girl.

