I'll have to check out the Wiki entry for Rangers. So far, it seems to me,
that most everything you write is well-researched, and it's not like I
haven't also investigated the history of amphibious warfare. :-) I'd be
curious as to what in that entry the other aspiring author did not like. Or
more to the point, what he did not like about what you wrote. Even on the US
Army Ranger Association website ( http://www.ranger.org/history.html ) it's
acknowledged that the Ranger concept does not originate with Roger's
Rangers - they ascribe the US Ranger tradition back to the mid or late
1600's. Considering that, and their function at the time, it's impossible
that they would not have copied what the French were doing.

I have looked at the naval gunfire support page on Wiki. It's not
particularly good - you will probably agree. For starters, there is no
"Modern" era - that would be best broken down a bit. Additionally, if a NGLO
is going to be mentioned, it wouldn't hurt to say that the Marine artillery
battalion supplies virtually all of the SFCP and liaison team, with Marine
people. In real world cases nobody on the green side may be USN at all.

I'd also seriously rework the paragraph that is much more opinion than
fact - namely, the editorial about battleships. I myself might even agree
with the tone of that, but I'd have to recognize that I am biased, and it is
not fact - it's opinion.

As to the continued NGFS training section of the Wiki, I propose calling
that just NGFS training, as a top level heading, and then having eras and/or
countries under that. What's in there right now I could totally demolish,
honestly - it's none of it that well-written, and some of it is biased. Hope
you didn't write some of that. :-) Because I am going to rework it.

AHS
