I've never written anything in the NGFS entry. I would recomend
reading "Naval Gunfire Support of Amphibious Operations: Past, Present
and Future" a 1977 study with concentration on Normandy, Iwo Jima and
Korea. It's a 54 MB download from the archives at the Marine Corps
University.
They also have downloadable copies of all the old NGFS FMs as well as
results of all the Gunnery Exercises of the 1920s and 1930s.
Another good source would be the relevant "Operations Research Group
Sudies" from WWII (16,17,29,30,47,48,251,252). These are either joint
US or combined US/British studies.
Some questions/musings I've had on NGFS in history:
I read an account of two attempts by the Portuguese to take a Moorish
fort, one unsuccessfully without NGFS and one successfully with. I
wonder if the timing of the first use of NGFS from ships in general
corresponds with the beginnings of the Portuguese empire and if NGFS
was a critical part of their success.
The Russian General Yudenich made good use of NGFS in a non-amphibious
landing context in 1916 against the Turks. He withdrew most of his
troops from contact in the area of his main effort but left his
artillery while he took his troops along the Black Sea coast covered
by NGFS to attack the Turks and open up shorter supply lines to his
main effort.
Naval gunfire raids against enemy positions were used in the Pacific,
but never in the ETO. Why didn't the navies in the ETO perform a
coastal gunfire campaign to attrit the German coastal defenses at the
same time as the aerial campaign that was used to block German
reinforcement?

